+### Why does Hive ship its own Ruby?
+
+Homebrew, AUR, and the portable installer all consume the same release artifacts,
+including the runtime and native gems. This makes the CLI, daemon, and TUI behave
+the same on tier-1 machines and avoids taking ownership of a user's system Ruby,
+Bundler, or source checkout.
+
 ## Troubleshooting
 
+### Another program already owns `hive`
+
+The portable installer preserves it and installs Hive as `hv`; internal child
+commands continue to use the package-owned executable. An Arch package-level
+conflict over `/usr/bin/hive` cannot be solved by PATH selection: keep the other
+package and use the portable `hv` channel, or remove the conflicting package
+explicitly. Hive never forces an overwrite.
+
+### Service registration failed after init
+
+The project is still initialized. Fix the reported launchd/systemd-user issue and
+run `hive daemon service install`; do not rerun `hive init`. `service status` and
+`service remove` are idempotent, and customized unit drift is preserved.
+
+### Uninstall must not remove project work
+
+Start with `hive uninstall --dry-run --json`. Core uninstall preserves all
+`.hive-state/` work and XDG workflow state, including with `--purge --yes`.
+Generated `.hive/project.yml` metadata requires the separate
+`--project-metadata` scope and consent. Agent packages remain agent-owned.
+
 ### `already initialized`
 
 Cause: the project already has a `hive/state` branch. Fix: skip `hive init` or use the existing `.hive-state/`. Exit code: 2.
