+## ADR-028: Tagged releases contain a pinned Tebako runtime and canonical assets
+
+**Status:** Active
+
+**Context:** The first packaging attempt used an unpinned Tebako install on stock runners, then abandoned the self-contained executable when native dependencies failed. A RubyGem fallback made installation depend on a compatible system Ruby, so Homebrew, AUR, and the bash installer no longer shared the runtime contract promised to users.
+
+**Decision:** Tier-1 release artifacts are built with Tebako 0.14.0 and embedded Ruby 3.4.2. `packaging/build/Dockerfile.tebako` is the single builder definition: it pins the Linux image by digest and supplies the Tebako/Ruby values consumed by both workflows and the macOS native build. Final metadata records the builder image digest and definition hash. The only published targets are `arm64-darwin` and `x86_64-linux-gnu`. Archives include the executable and `share/hive/{templates,schemas,examples,wiki}`, deterministic build metadata, and no system-Ruby fallback. The packer smoke removes Ruby from `PATH` before exercising the CLI, doctor, daemon, native TUI, native gems, and runtime assets.
+
+**Consequences:** Packaging failure blocks release instead of changing the product contract. The Linux artifact targets glibc 2.31+ and is tested on Ubuntu and Arch. Every channel can consume one archive shape, while release metadata records the exact packer, embedded Ruby, source commit, source epoch, and executable hash. Native CI evidence remains a release gate; source tests cannot substitute for executing each artifact on its target host.
+
+## ADR-029: XDG owns global control files; `.hive-state/` remains durable project state
+
+**Status:** Active
+
+**Context:** Global registry, daemon state, logs, and installed assets were coupled to a source checkout at `~/Dev/hive`, while packaged execution needs stable user and package-manager locations. Renaming or moving `.hive-state/`, however, would break active task folders, orphan-branch worktree metadata, project-local agent context, and accumulated history.
+
+**Decision:** `Hive::Paths` resolves XDG config/data/state/cache and keeps `HIVE_HOME` as a collapsed compatibility/test override. Empty XDG variables are unset. Legacy `~/Dev/hive/config.yml` is atomically copied once and retained. New projects commit `.hive/project.yml` with schema version 1 and a `state_worktree` pointer; runtime reads it before the legacy literal. `.hive-state/` remains the default durable orphan worktree. `Hive::Assets` owns built-in template, schema, service, and script lookup across source, executable-relative, XDG, Homebrew, and system prefixes.
+
+**Consequences:** Global files no longer require a source checkout, package channels can install assets under native prefixes, and legacy projects continue to run without migration. Invalid project pointers, path traversal, symlink escape, missing explicit asset roots, and partial `.hive/` collisions fail before state mutation. Project work/history is never moved or deleted.
+
+## ADR-030: One strict release manifest is canonical for every install channel
+
+**Status:** Active
+
+**Context:** Independently generated checksums and package recipes can publish the same version label with different bytes, target names, runtime contents, or source commits. Tag-only packaging also lets an untested builder failure appear after an immutable version is announced.
+
+**Decision:** `packaging/release/manifest.yml` closes the tier-1 target set and required archive paths. `packaging/release/finalize.rb` accepts only an exact `vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`/`Hive::VERSION` pair, requires both artifacts, checks executable mode and runtime assets, and refuses target/version/builder/Ruby/source-commit disagreement. Its signed `SHA256SUMS` authenticates the archives, `release.json`, `install.sh`, and `install.sh.sha256`; provenance attestations cover the archives plus the manifest/bootstrap assets. A signed tag first creates a public prerelease explicitly marked non-latest. Only after Homebrew/AUR publication and every tier-1 lifecycle/native-agent acceptance job pass is that candidate promoted to the latest stable release.
+
+**Consequences:** No channel may synthesize its own artifact identity. Publication is impossible before both Ruby-free native smokes, manifest finalization, checksum verification, keyless signature, and GitHub provenance attestation succeed. Existing tags are verified and never moved; a live release requires a source version whose tag is still free.
+
+## ADR-031: Installation receipts own lifecycle; workflow state is never uninstall-owned
+
+**Status:** Active
+
+**Context:** PATH inspection cannot distinguish Hive from Apache Hive, and self-updating a binary managed by Homebrew or pacman violates manager ownership. Broad directory deletion is also unacceptable because XDG state and `.hive-state/` contain accumulated work, not disposable installation files.
+
+**Decision:** Every managed channel writes a schema-1 JSON receipt naming the channel, package identity, chosen command, stable executable, asset root, version, service identity, and owned files. Auto-discovery reads every candidate and rejects distinct installations; an explicit `HIVE_INSTALL_RECEIPT` is the only override. `InstallChannel::Lifecycle` owns channel commands, manager helpers, result handling, bash layout, and prefix reuse. Bash wrapper deletion requires a currently matching symlink into the validated version payload, and payload removal is contained to one direct `versions/` child. Update delegates to the owning manager or one cosign-authenticated immutable installer tag. Uninstall completes service deregistration first, then removes only manager/receipt-owned core files. `--purge --yes` may remove config/cache but never XDG state or any `.hive-state/`; `.hive/project.yml` requires separate scope and consent.
+
+**Consequences:** An unrelated `hive` earlier on PATH cannot capture internal subprocesses, native managers retain exclusive control of upgrades/removal, malformed receipts never fall through to a different updater, and automated purge remains work-preserving. Agent plugins, marketplaces, provider credentials, and host auth stores are outside core ownership.
+
+## ADR-032: First-run configuration is isolated to one explicit agent host
+
+**Status:** Active
+
+**Context:** Source defaults span Claude and Codex roles. Applying those defaults on a clean Codex-only or Pi-only workstation made `hive doctor` fail on an agent the operator deliberately did not install, while non-TTY init could silently write cross-host roles after an active-host-only marketplace setup.
+
+**Decision:** First-run automation passes `--agent-host claude|codex|pi` to both `hive doctor` and `hive init`. Doctor rebinds all role and reviewer probes to that host and, before init, checks its supported defaults: `ce-code-review` on every host and PR Review Toolkit on Claude only. Non-TTY init renders every stage/review role and the host-supported reviewer set for that host. Without the flag, the longstanding interactive/mixed-host defaults remain unchanged.
+
+**Consequences:** A green pre-init doctor proves the package set needed by the config that init will actually write. Active-host setup never requires or mutates another agent home, while operators who intentionally want mixed agents retain the existing interactive/config paths.
+
